2026-04-21 01:40:00 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main lamp (load module)'] hypothesis_explanation='Supply module is stable: its LED is continuously on and ~11.8–12 V is present. Control module is stable: adjusting timing and sensitivity has no effect on the 20‑s blink, and measurements show a constant ~11.85 V at the relay output regardless of the flicker, so the relay and sensor circuitry are not periodically interrupting power. The same stable voltage is measured at the load module input during the blink, so cabling and connectors are intact. Yet both the main lamp and the parallel indicator lamp extinguish together for about 0.5 s every 20 s.\n\nGiven constant input voltage and no switching upstream, the only remaining plausible location for a periodic interruption of current is inside the load module itself. Because the indicator lamp is in parallel with the main lamp and both go dark together while the input voltage remains, the series diode and common wiring must be momentarily going open/high‑impedance. That behavior is characteristic of an intermittent internal fault (e.g., thermal or mechanical) in the load assembly—most likely the main lamp element or its internal connection, which also interrupts current to the parallel indicator.\n\nTherefore the root cause is an internal intermittent/open fault in the load module’s main lamp assembly (including its immediate internal wiring/socket), and the corrective action should be to repair/replace that main lamp module/component.'
