2026-04-21 01:40:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module battery (12 V source)'] hypothesis_explanation='The control-module output and the load-module input both remain at ~11.8 V even during the half‑second OFF intervals, and the series protection diode in the load module remains forward‑biased with a normal drop, while both bulbs themselves have already been proven not faulty. This means the wiring, relay contacts, diode, and lamps are providing a continuous circuit. The only remaining element that can cause a periodic, brief loss of current without an observed local open circuit is the energy source sagging below the lamps’ sustaining voltage and recovering. A weak or intermittently failing 12 V battery will allow its terminal voltage to droop under steady load until an internal protection/chemistry effect makes the current momentarily collapse (lamp goes out), then it recovers, repeating roughly every 20 s. Since all downstream components behave normally and full voltage is only confirmed under light load measurements, the most plausible root cause is a degraded or faulty battery in the power supply module. Replacing the 12 V battery should eliminate the periodic blinking.'
