2026-04-21 01:40:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient light sensor (control module)', 'timing/sensitivity potentiometers (control module)', 'sensor amplifier / relay‑driver circuit (control module)'] hypothesis_explanation="Measurements show that the power‑supply module is solid (LED steady, battery replaced with no effect) and that the control‑module relay output remains at ~11.85 V without any drop during the half‑second lamp outage. The load‑module input also remains at ~11.84 V and the series diode has a normal, stable ~0.77 V forward drop during the blink. Both the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp are confirmed good. This rules out the power source, cabling polarity, relay contacts, series diode, and the lamps themselves.\n\nTherefore the only remaining plausible cause of a stable 20‑second, 0.5‑second OFF flicker—with the simulation explicitly flagging an 'unstable or oscillating state'—is an internal instability in the ambient‑light sensor control electronics: the light sensor, its timing/sensitivity potentiometers, and the amplifier/relay‑driver network that determines the relay state. A leaky sensor, mis‑biased comparator, or faulty RC timing network can make the control circuit oscillate or periodically reset while still holding the relay apparently closed on average, so that the main 12 V path to the load never measures fully open with a simple meter, yet the lamp current briefly collapses at the observed interval.\n\nBecause all other modules and components have been ruled out by direct replacement or measurements, the root cause is most likely an internal fault or mis‑bias in the control module’s sensor/driver section. Replacing or repairing the ambient light sensor circuit (including its RC timing network and associated potentiometers / comparator stage) should eliminate the 20‑second oscillatory blink."
