2026-04-21 01:40:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['switched‑cables indicator LED circuit (control module)', 'associated series resistor / wiring for switched‑cables indicator (control module)'] hypothesis_explanation='All power‑path components have been verified healthy: the PSU provides a stable ~11.8 V, the control‑module relay output remains at full voltage during the 20‑s blink, the load‑module input and series diode both maintain correct voltage, and both the main lamp and internal lamp indicator in the load module are sound. The relay driver, timing and sensitivity network, and ambient light sensor have also been ruled out as faulty by prior replacement. The inter‑module wiring and polarities are correct. Yet the simulation reports the circuit is in an unstable/oscillating state.\n\nThe only remaining active circuit not yet tested or replaced is the \x13\x13"switched cables indicator" LED/resistor network in the control module, which is connected between the switched positive line and the negative reference. If that indicator circuit is mis‑biased or partially shorting (for example, an incorrect resistor value, intermittent LED junction behavior, or leakage path), it can introduce a slow charge/discharge interaction with the relay‑driver reference or local supply that does not pull the 12 V rail down (hence the constant 11.8 V measured at the module outputs) but periodically perturbs the internal reference used by the sensor amplifier. That would cause the relay drive to momentarily release or the lamp current path to be briefly interrupted every ~20 seconds, manifesting exactly as the observed half‑second OFF blink while all measured node voltages appear nominal.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a fault in the switched‑cables indicator LED circuit (LED and/or series resistor / wiring) within the control module, creating an internal oscillation without affecting the external DC levels.'
