2026-04-21 01:41:08 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['inter‑module fast‑connection terminals between control module output (+/−) and load module input (+/−)'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components (battery, power LED circuit, control sensor/amplifier/relay, timing and sensitivity potentiometers, both load lamps, and the load‑module diode) have been individually tested or virtually replaced with no effect, and the measured voltages are stable: ~11.85 V is continuously present at the control‑module relay output and at the load‑module input, even during the half‑second lamp outage. The diode forward drop also remains normal during the blink. This rules out an internal intermittent open or oscillation inside any module.\n\nWhat can still cause the lamp to extinguish briefly while the meter continues to read full supply at the module terminals is an intermittent, high‑resistance, or momentary open contact specifically at the fast‑connection terminals that bridge the control module output to the load module input. A loose or oxidized contact can remain conductive enough for a DMM reading (especially if the meter leads are making better contact than the load path) yet drop current under load, causing the lamps to go out. Slight vibration, thermal cycling, or internal spring action in these plug connectors can readily produce a quasi‑periodic interruption on the order of tens of seconds.\n\nAll previous inspections focused on polarity and gross mis‑wiring and did not repair or replace the terminal hardware itself. Therefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a faulty or marginal pair of fast‑connection terminals between the control‑module output and the load‑module input. Replacing or refurbishing this terminal pair should eliminate the 20‑second periodic lamp dropout.'
