2026-04-21 01:41:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contacts (power path through relay)'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules show a steady ~11.8–11.9 V from the power supply through the control‑module output to the load‑module input, even during the half‑second OFF interval of the lamp. The sensor, timing/sensitivity network, relay driver electronics, lamps, load‑module diode and wiring, inter‑module cabling, and PSU/battery have all effectively been ruled out by prior targeted replacements/tests. The simulation notes an ‘unstable or oscillating state’, yet no variation is detected on the DC supply rails or the control‑module output voltage. \n\nThe only remaining element that can intermittently interrupt current to the lamp without showing a significant change in measured terminal voltage is a mechanical problem in the relay’s power contacts themselves: pitted/oxidized or misaligned contacts that momentarily increase contact resistance or open under load, but still allow the meter to read nearly full open‑circuit voltage. This would present exactly as a brief lamp outage every ~20 s while all DC measurements at the terminals appear normal. \n\nThus the most plausible root cause is a faulty set of relay power contacts inside the control module, while the relay coil/driver and the rest of the circuit remain functional. Replacing or repairing the relay contact block (or the entire relay) should eliminate the periodic lamp flicker.'
