2026-04-21 01:41:35 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['lamp protection diode in load module (series diode ahead of both bulbs)', 'load module internal wiring around series diode and lamp connections'] hypothesis_explanation='All measured supply points (PSU output, control input, control output, and load input) remain at a steady ~11.8 V during the periodic half‑second OFF of the lamp, so the interruption is not due to the battery, wiring between modules, relay drive circuitry, or relay contacts. The control module’s operation and sensor/timing network have already been ruled out by both functional tests and a failed repair attempt. The main lamp and the indicator lamp themselves have also been replaced/tested with no effect, which points to a series element common to both lamps. The only such element is the series protection diode in the load module, together with its immediate wiring/solder joints.\n\nYour earlier voltage test on the diode captured a normal forward drop (~0.77 V from 11.83 V anode to 11.06 V cathode), but it was effectively a spot check; an intermittent internal open or high‑resistance fault in the diode junction or its connections could easily present normal readings most of the time and then momentarily open every ~20 seconds, extinguishing both lamps while leaving the upstream 12 V nodes unchanged. The simulator’s note about the circuit being in an ‘unstable or oscillating state’ is consistent with a marginal, thermally or current‑dependent series element rather than a logic‑driven relay action.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is an intermittent fault in the load‑module series protection diode or its immediate wiring, causing brief open‑circuit conditions to both bulbs while all module supply voltages stay stable. Replacing/repairing the diode and its connections should eliminate the periodic 20‑second half‑second outage of the lamp.'
