2026-04-21 01:42:38 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['external environment / ambient lighting around control module light sensor (periodic disturbance every ~20 s)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show a completely steady 11.8–11.9 V from the battery through the control module to the load module, and a constant 0.113 A flowing into the load module with no variation during the observed 0.5 s “OFF” events. Both the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp in the load module share the same series diode and supply; that diode’s forward drop is steady (≈0.77 V) with no open‑circuit episodes. The relay contacts and driver circuitry in the control module have been functionally cleared: the relay is closed, its output voltage is constant, and replacing the sensor, amplifier, driver, timing/sensitivity potentiometers, and relay contacts had no effect. Cables, polarities, and fast‑connection terminals between modules have also been inspected and/or functionally ruled out.\n\nTherefore there is no intermittent electrical interruption inside any of the three modules or their interconnections. The only remaining element that can produce a repeatable ~20 s change in the apparent lamp brightness, while electrical power and current remain constant, is a periodic change in the *external* optical environment—specifically, the ambient illumination that both (a) is being monitored by the system’s light sensor and (b) is used by the human observer to decide whether the lamp is perceived as ON or OFF. A slow, roughly 20‑second external disturbance (for example, another timed light source, an automatic dimming system, or a moving/shuttering object modulating the observer’s view of the lamp) would periodically overwhelm or obscure the lamp’s light, making it appear to go dark for about 0.5 s even though its electrical drive and optical output remain steady.\n\nGiven that every internal component and connection tested or replaced has proven healthy, the root cause is best explained as a periodic external ambient‑lighting disturbance around the control module and lamp, not an internal circuit fault.'
